ode value="gweb"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Social Media</CodeD><CodeI org="categoriser" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="es-EnglishNS_en_20180320142642"/><CodeA name="es_score" value="160"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="2"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gcat"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Political/General News</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gweb"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="glife"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Living/Lifestyle</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gweb"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Opinion</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">The Straits Times says; Facing up to the ills of social media</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>The quandary presented by the "Delete Facebook" movement reveals the extent to which Internet users have become enmeshed in the Matrix-like world of online data. Leaving Facebook, to protest its excesses, is not all that easy, especially if an account is to be permanently deleted - it can take up to 90 days to delete everything. Exiting could affect the use of handy apps and sites accessed via one's Facebook account. And getting cut off from far-flung family members and friends, who are part of Facebook's 2.2 billion users, can be irksome when alternative platforms do not appeal to individuals. It can pose practical problems too for non-users, when an employer or a landlord relies on Facebook profiles to do checks, and organisations use it to schedule meetings and to create and manage events.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Social media giants have indeed become deeply embedded in people's lives, and the power that lies in their hands was bestowed on them by users themselves. Lured by the conveniences and diversions offered, people voluntarily surrendered considerable personal data to these companies in many cases. In others, they were egged on by apps to release their contacts. Consequently, Facebook and app owners can produce "shadow profiles" of even non-users, created by scrutinising information given by their friends and other sources. That is how the voter-profiling company at the centre of the latest data scandal, Cambridge Analytica, could obtain dossiers on 50 million Facebook users from a profiling app downloaded by just 270,000 people.</Para><Para>How could so much be accumulated without any accounts being hacked? Part of the bitter truth is that data was handed to the Internet giants on a silver platter because people were not discriminating enough about privacy. And partly, it was because these behemoths grew too big for their boots while regulators stood on the sidelines, somewhat at a loss. Facebook got away in 2014 with secret psychological tests to manipulate emotions, conducted two years earlier on almost 700,000 users. In 2015, Facebook learnt of the unauthorised data mining that took place in the Cambridge Analytica case, but kept silent about it till the malpractices were exposed by mainstream media this month.</Para><Para>Their own actions show that social media giants cannot be relied upon to weigh the wider consequences of data misuse and to regulate themselves. Few would object to the mining of anonymised user information for Big Data innovation that benefits the community. But illicit data harvesting must be prevented, especially when it's for the purpose of influencing elections via covert methods - like altering the mood of voters and allowing disinformation campaigns. Without oversight, social media will sharply divide groups even as it connects people like never before.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field"></Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

